n|36\n|[[Thomas Harrison (Royal Navy officer)|Thomas Harrison]]\n|240\n|\n|-\n|''[[HMS Minerva (1759)|Minerva]]''\n|32\n|[[Alexander Hood, 1st Viscount Bridport|Alexander Hood]]\n|220\n|\n|-\n|''[[HMS Sapphire (1741)|Sapphire]]''\n|32\n|[[Sir John Strachan, 5th Baronet|John Strachan]]\n|220\n|\n|-\n|''[[HMS Vengeance (1758)|Vengeance]]''\n|28\n|[[Sir Gamaliel Nightingale, 9th Baronet|Gamaliel Nightingale]]\n|200\n|\n|-\n|''[[HMS Coventry (1757)|Coventry]]''\n|28\n|Francis Burslem\n|200\n|\n|-\n|''[[HMS Maidstone (1758)|Maidstone]]''\n|28\n|Dudley Digges\n|200\n|\n|}<!-- With thanks to the authors of the French page on this battle -->\n\n==Namesake==\n[[HMAS Quiberon (G81)|HMAS ''Quiberon'']] was a [[destroyer]] named in memory of the battle of Quiberon Bay. She served in the [[Royal Navy]] and then the [[Royal Australian Navy]]. ''Quiberon'' was launched in 1942 and saw operations in World War II. She was decommissioned in 1964.{{sfn|Cassells|2000|p=}}\n\n==Notes, citations and sources==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Anderson\n|first=Fred\n|date=2001\n|title=Crucible of War: The Seven Years' War and the Fate of Empire in British North America, 1754\u20131766\n|url=\n|location=London\n|publisher=Faber and Faber\n|page=\n|isbn=978-0571205653\n|author-link=Fred Anderson (historian)\n\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cassells |first=Vic |title=The Destroyers: their battles and their badges |year=2000 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=East Roseville, New South Wales |isbn=0-7318-0893-2 |oclc=46829686|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| volume =\n| issue =53\n| pages =17\u201329\n| last =Chaline\n| first =Oliver\n| language=Fr\n| title =Quiberon Bay, 20 Novembre 1759\n| journal =Les cahiers du Pays de Gu\u00e9rande\n|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Amis de Gu\u00e9rande\n| date =2011\n| issn =0765-3565\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=la Condamine\n|first=Pierre de\n|date=2000\n| language=Fr\n|title=Le combat des Cardinaux : 20 novembre 1759, baie de Quiberon et rade du Croisic\n|url=\n|location=La Turballe\n|publisher= L'Esprit large-\u00c9d. Aliz\u00e9s\n|page=\n|isbn=978-2911835032\n|author-link=\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{citation | title=England In The Seven Years War vol II | first=Julian S. | last=Corbett | publisher=Longmans Green | year=1907 | url=https://archive.org/stream/englandinsevenye02corb/englandinsevenye02corb_djvu.txt }}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Dull\n|first=Jonathan R.\n|date=2009\n|title=The Age of the Ship of the Line: the British and French Navies, 1650\u20131815\n|url=\n|location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire\n|publisher=Pen & Sword Books\n|page=\n|isbn=978-1848325494\n|author-link=\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Jenkins\n|first=E.H.\n|date=1973\n|title=A History of the French Navy : From its Beginnings to the Present Day\n|url=\n|location=London\n|publisher=Macdonald and Jane\u015b\n|page=\n|isbn=978-0356041964\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last= Mahan\n|first=Alfred Thayer Mahan\n|date=1890\n|title=The Influence of Sea Power upon History, 1660\u20131783\n\n|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Influence_of_Sea_Power_upon_History/Chapter_VIII\n|chapter=VIII\n|location=London\n|publisher=Sampson, Low, Marston\n|page=\n|oclc=782063369\n|author-link=Alfred Thayer Mahan\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=McLynn\n|first=Frank\n|date=2005\n|title=1759: the Year Britain Became Master of the World\n|url=\n|location=London\n|publisher=Pimlico\n|page=\n|isbn=978-0099526391\n|author-link=Frank McLynn\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=le Moing\n|first=Guy\n|date=2003\n|title=La Bataille Navale des Cardinaux: 20 novembre 1759\n|url=\n|location=Paris\n|publisher=Economica\n|page=\n|isbn=978-2717845037\n|lang=Fr\n|author-link=\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Monod\n|first=Paul Kl\u00e9ber\n|date=2009\n|title=Imperial Island: A History of Britain and Its Empire, 1660\u20131837\n|url=\n|location=Malden, Massachusetts